title: Week 7 high school football roundup
text:
Week 7 high school football roundup Tim Walters , FLORIDA TODAY 12:20 a.m. EDT October 10, 2015 Buy Photo Brian Lankford-Johnson of Palm Bay runs in traffic during Friday's game against Viera. (Photo: Craig Bailey, Craig Bailey/FLORIDA TODAY) Buy Photo CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
PALM BAY 40, VIERA 35 
In Viera, Palm Bay opened a three-touchdown lead in the first half, but had to hold on to defeat Viera. 
Brian Lankford-Johnson rushed for 280 yards and four touchdowns to lead the way for Palm Bay. 
Viera had a chance to win the game at the end, with the ball at the 25 and 10 seconds remaining. 
After a pass fell incomplete, the Hawks had one more chance with one second remaining. 
But Palm Bay’s defense got to Viera QB Hayden Kingston, hitting his arm as he threw. The pass was a wobbly ball completed at the 8-yard line, but time ran out on the Hawks and Palm Bay took the W. 
ROCKLEDGE 20, ASTRONAUT 7 
In Rockledge, the Raiders rebounded from a tough loss last week by dropping Astronaut at home. 
Running backs Jalen Mitchell and Keith Freeman and quarterback Jacquez Lyons shouldered the load offensively for Rockledge. 
Mitchell rushed for a game-high 94 yards, Freeman rushed for a touchdown and caught another, and Lyons ran for a score and threw one to Freeman. Rockledge holds on against Astronaut 
SEBASTIAN RIVER 39, BAYSIDE 9 
In Palm Bay, despite being beaten badly again, Bayside fought to the bitter end, scoring its lone touchdown just before the game’s clock hit zero. 
D’Andre Edwards fought his way through a group of Sebastian River defenders and into the end zone to add to the lone field goal the Bears got just before the half. 
The Bears are still looking for their first win of the season and will try to get that win on the road next Friday, traveling to Okeechobee for another district game. 
EAU GALLIE 35, COCOA BEACH 0 
In Melbourne, Eau Gallie shut out Cocoa Beach, and scored five touchdowns without throwing a pass. 
Tyvone Brooks led the Commodores in rushing with 14 carries for 165 yards, but Jalen Shelton wasn’t far behind with seven carries for 126 yards. 
Brooks ran in two touchdowns for Eau Gallie, with Shelton running in the other three. 
HERITAGE 44, MELBOURNE 0 
In Palm Bay, Heritage’s defense was smothering, leading the way for the Panthers. 
Just how stifling was their defense? The Panthers forced four turnovers, scored nine points on their own and held the Bulldogs to eight total yards in the first half. 
Daeshawn Mills led Heritage offensively with 102 yards on 12 carries and a touchdown. 
HOLY TRINITY 44, AGAPE CHRISTIAN 28 
In Melbourne, Holy Trinity running back Jashaun Corbin rushed for a game-high 259 yards and five touchdowns. 
The wild win wasn’t secured until Tiger defensive tackle Andre Neuharth rumbled 12 yards with a fumble recovery for a TD with 4:47 remaining. 
After a season opening loss, the Tigers have reeled off five consecutive wins, thanks in large part to the exploits of Corbin. The speedy sophomore, who entered the contest leading Brevard rushers with 785 yards, scored in every quarter on TD runs of 27, 2, 1, 39 and 40 yards. 
While Corbin is earning a reputation for his offensive feats, it may have been his acrobatic interception in the third quarter that gave the Tigers momentum early in the second half. Corbin’s theft led to his fourth touchdown with 6:39 remaining in the third quarter. 
“It felt good; me and Joc (Perry) are having a competition to see who can get the most picks and I’m winning right now,” said Corbin. “I’ve got two, but I also have a pick-six.”
